ort-lived, and usually followed by disgruntlement and even cynicism about the actual operation of democratic institutions. It is widely accepted that democracy is a good thing. However democrats have much work to do in improving the performance of democratic institutions. The essays in this volume focus on this difficult and vital challenge: how can we improve the design of democratic institutions? How can public deliberation in democracies be enhanced? How can elections be reformed so as to dampen the excessive influence of special interests, especially those with money? How can democratic institutions be reformed so they can deal with issues that transcend the boundaries of the nation-state? And finally, how can democratic practices better take account of the internal plurality of societies that are ethnically or otherwise divided? Contributors: Brooke Ackerly, Ian Ayres, Geoffrey Brennan, John Ferejohn, Alan Hamlin, Russell Hardin, Donald Horowitz, Stephen Macedo, Philip Petit, Philippe C. Schmitter, Ian Shapiro, Philippe Van Parjis, Iris Marion Young.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDemocracy. 0aDemocratization. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh1 aAckerly, Brooke A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAyres, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrennan, Geoffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerejohn, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamlin, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHardin, Russell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorowitz, Donald L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacedo, Stephen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.go